

Today we'll learn one of the **most frequently asked interview topics**:

# 🚀 Call by Value vs Call by Reference

This topic answers a question you've probably had:

> "If I change a variable inside a function, why doesn't the original variable change?"

---

# 🧠 Concept 1: Call by Value

## ✅ What is Call by Value?

When you pass a variable to a function, C sends a **copy** of the value.

```c
void fun(int x) {
    x = 100;
}
```

---

## 💡 Real-World Analogy

Imagine you give your friend a **photocopy of your notes** 📄.

Your friend writes on the photocopy.

Will your original notes change?

❌ No.

Because they modified the copy.

---

## 💻 Example

```c
#include <stdio.h>

void change(int x) {
    x = 100;
}

int main() {
    int a = 10;

    change(a);

    printf("%d", a);

    return 0;
}
```

Output:

```text
10
```

---

## ⚙️ Why?

Memory visualization:

```text
main:
a = 10

change:
x = 10   (copy)
```

When:

```c
x = 100;
```

Only the copy changes.

Original remains:

```text
a = 10
```

---

## 🧠 Memory Trick

Remember:

**"Call by Value = function gets a photocopy."**

---

# 🔥 Interview Question

### Can a function modify the original variable using Call by Value?

Answer:

❌ No.

Because it only receives a copy.

---

# 🧠 Concept 2: Call by Reference (Using Pointers)

## ✅ What is Call by Reference?

Instead of sending the value,

👉 we send the **address**.

Now the function can directly access the original variable.

---

## 💡 Real-World Analogy

Instead of giving a photocopy,

you give your friend the **house address** 🏠.

Now they can go directly to your house and change things there.

---

## 💻 Example

```c
#include <stdio.h>

void change(int *p) {
    *p = 100;
}

int main() {

    int a = 10;

    change(&a);

    printf("%d", a);

    return 0;
}
```

Output:

```text
100
```

---

# ⚙️ Step-by-Step Understanding

Initially:

```text
a = 10
address = 1000
```

Function call:

```c
change(&a);
```

sends:

```text
1000
```

Inside function:

```c
int *p = 1000;
```

Now:

```c
*p = 100;
```

means:

> Go to address 1000 and store 100.

Original variable changes.

---

# 🔥 Golden Visualization

```text
a = 10
|
Address = 1000

p = 1000

*p = 10
```

After:

```c
*p = 100;
```

```text
a = 100
```

---

## 🧠 Memory Trick

Remember:

**"Call by Reference = function gets the house address."**

---

# ⚠️ Important Truth About C

Many interviewers ask:

### Does C support Call by Reference?

Strictly speaking:

❌ No.

C only supports:

✅ Call by Value

But we simulate reference behavior by passing addresses (pointers).

This is a favorite interview question.

---

# 🎯 Comparison Table

| Call by Value      | Call by Reference   |
| ------------------ | ------------------- |
| Copy sent          | Address sent        |
| Original unchanged | Original can change |
| Safer              | More powerful       |
| No pointers needed | Uses pointers       |

---

# 💻 Example: Swapping Numbers

### Without Pointers

```c
void swap(int a, int b)
{
    int temp = a;
    a = b;
    b = temp;
}
```

❌ Doesn't swap original variables.

---

### With Pointers

```c
void swap(int *a, int *b)
{
    int temp = *a;

    *a = *b;
    *b = temp;
}
```

✅ Original variables swap correctly.

---

# 🔥 Why Interviewers Love This Topic

Because it checks whether you understand:

* Variables
* Memory
* Addresses
* Pointers
* Function calls

All together.

---

# 🎯 Most Asked Placement Questions

### Q1

Why doesn't this work?

```c
swap(a,b);
```

Answer:

Because copies are passed.

---

### Q2

Why does this work?

```c
swap(&a,&b);
```

Answer:

Addresses are passed.

---

### Q3

Can C truly do Call by Reference?

Answer:

No.

It uses Call by Value of addresses.

---

# 🔗 Connection to What You Already Know

Previously:

```c
int *p = &a;
```

stored an address.

Today you learned:

👉 Passing that address into a function lets the function modify the original variable.

This is the main practical use of pointers.

